05043nam a22006255i 9780226762777DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267627777 a10.7208/97802267627772doi  a(DE-B1597)524106  a(OCoLC)769628622  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQH506b.C73 2011 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a572.80922300aCreating a Physical Biology :bThe Three-Man Paper and Early Molecular Biology /ced. by Brandon Fogel, Phillip R. Sloan. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b9 halftones, 11 line drawings, 14 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tPart I. Historical Origins of the Three-Man Paper -- tChapter 2. Physics and Genes: From Einstein to Delbrück -- tChapter 3. Biophysics in Berlin: The Delbrück Club -- tChapter 4. Exhuming the Three-Man Paper: Target-Theoretical Research in the 1930s and 1940s -- tPart II. Philosophical Perspectives on the Three-Man Paper -- tChapter 5. Niels Bohr and Max Delbrück: Balancing Autonomy and Reductionism in Biology -- tChapter 6. Was Delbrück a Reductionist? -- tPart III. The Three-Man Paper -- tTranslator’s Preface -- tThe Text of the Three-Man Paper -- tReferences in the Three-Man Paper -- tCombined Bibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1935 geneticist Nikolai Timoféeff-Ressovsky, radiation physicist Karl G. Zimmer, and quantum physicist Max Delbrück published “On the Nature of Gene Mutation and Gene Structure,” known subsequently as the “Three-Man Paper.” This seminal paper advanced work on the physical exploration of the structure of the gene through radiation physics and suggested ways in which physics could reveal definite information about gene structure, mutation, and action. Representing a new level of collaboration between physics and biology, it played an important role in the birth of the new field of molecular biology. The paper’s results were popularized for a wide audience in the What is Life? lectures of physicist Erwin Schrödinger in 1944. Despite its historical impact on the biological sciences, the paper has remained largely inaccessible because it was only published in a short-lived German periodical. Creating a Physical Biology makes the Three Man Paper available in English for the first time. Brandon Fogel’s translation is accompanied by an introductory essay by Fogel and Phillip Sloan and a set of essays by leading historians and philosophers of biology that explore the context, contents, and subsequent influence of the paper, as well as its importance for the wider philosophical analysis of biological reductionism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGeneticsxHistoryx20th century. 0aGeneticsxHistoryy20th century. 0aMolecular biologyxHistoryx20th century. 0aMolecular biologyxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBarham, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyler, Richard H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFogel, Brandon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFogel, Brandon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcKaughan, Daniel J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoll-Hansen, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSloan, Phillip R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSloan, Phillip R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSummers, William C., econtributor.4ctb4h